🛠️ How to implement it (Unity‑friendly, Quest‑friendly)

1. Add a DiagnosticCanvas prefab
World‑space or screen‑space overlay.

Contains:

- A text field for the current step  
- A “Continue” button  
- A scrollable log window (optional)

2. Add a DiagnosticManager.cs
This script controls the sequence.

`csharp
public class DiagnosticManager : MonoBehaviour
{
    public Text stepText;
    public Button continueButton;

    private int step = 0;

    void Start()
    {
        ShowStep("Unity Scene Loaded");
    }

    public void Continue()
    {
        step++;

        switch (step)
        {
            case 1:
                ShowStep("XR Loader Initialised");
                // TODO: Try initialising XR here
                break;

            case 2:
                ShowStep("Passthrough Permission Granted");
                // TODO: Request permissions
                break;

            case 3:
                ShowStep("Passthrough Started");
                // TODO: Start passthrough
                break;

            case 4:
                ShowStep("AR Camera Active");
                break;

            case 5:
                ShowStep("HUD Loaded");
                break;

            case 6:
                ShowStep("Mode Controller Started");
                break;

            case 7:
                ShowStep("Path Tracker Active");
                break;

            case 8:
                ShowStep("Coverage Map Active");
                break;

            case 9:
                ShowStep("Entering Game");
                // TODO: Hide diagnostic UI and start real game
                break;
        }
    }

    void ShowStep(string text)
    {
        stepText.text = text;
    }
}
`

3. Add a “Diagnostic Mode” toggle
In Bootstrap.unity, add:

- A checkbox  
- Or a command‑line flag  
- Or a scriptable object setting  

When enabled, the game pauses all startup logic until the user presses “Continue”.

---

🧠 Why this works so well on Quest 3

Because the Quest 3:

- Does NOT show Unity logs  
- Does NOT show XR errors  
- Does NOT show permission failures  
- Does NOT show loader failures  

So you need a manual checkpoint system.

This gives you:

- A visible breadcrumb trail  
- A guaranteed UI even if XR fails  
- A way to isolate the exact failing subsystem  
- A way to test on‑device without ADB spam  

---

🎯 What this will tell us immediately

If your app currently shows:

- Dark grey window  
- No passthrough  
- No UI  

Then with Diagnostic Mode:

If Step 1 appears → Unity scene is fine

If Step 2 never appears → XR loader is failing

If Step 3 never appears → permission request is failing

If Step 4 never appears → passthrough is failing

If Step 5 never appears → AR camera is failing

This is exactly the kind of visibility you need.

